Title: Mechanical Diagnosis Using Classification: A Brake Diagnostic System  
Author: Richard Fox and Gilbert Ochoa 
Date: July 26, 1995  
Address: Pan American  
Affiliation: Department of Computer Science The University of Texas  
Pubnum: Technical Report  
Abstract: In this paper, we present a system to perform automated mechanical diagnosis of a car's brake system. The diagnostic process is performed by using the Generic Tasks of Hierarchcial Classification and Routine Recognition. A classification hierarchy is used to represent the possible malfunctions of a car's brake system. The two Generic Tasks are used to traverse the malfunction hierarchy in an attempt to establish the most likely malfunction hypothesis (or hypotheses) provided a description of the car's current condition as input. This paper details the Generic Tasks of Hierarchical Classification and Routine Recognition, provide an in depth description of the brake system, and offer an example of the brake system performing diagnosis. 
