Reference-contexts: The diagnostician uses the hierarchy as a search space to perform the diagnosis by seeking the most likely malfunctions within the hierarchy. And so, diagnosis is often synonymous with classification <ref> [4] </ref>. Automating the process of diagnosis requires the representation and utilization of diagnostic knowledge. Diagnostic knowledge usually takes on two forms, domain-specific knowledge and procedural knowledge. <p> Two of the earliest Generic Tasks identified, and two of the most commonly used Generic Tasks, are Hierarchical Classification and Routine Recognition. Classification <ref> [4] </ref> is the task of generating a particular instance or subtype of a given type by searching through a taxonomic hierarchy. Input to the classification task is some description of the object/concept in question and output are the subclasses or instances which best fit the described case.
